The number 21,811 is the value for the date &#39;19SEP2019&#39;d.  So just apply the DATE9 format to convert it.

    %let date_return=&quot;%sysfunc(putn(&amp;date_return,date9)):00:00:00&quot;dt;

Note that you can also use the optional second argument to the %SYSFUNC() function to tell it how to format the function results.

    %let data_return = %sysfunc(intnx(DAY,&amp;data_proc.,-1),date9);

Then you just need to tack on the `:00:00:00` suffix to make it look like datetime value instead of date value.

Note that you probably can eliminate most of this logic and just let INTNX() find the right day for you by using the WEEKDAY interval instead of DAY interval.

    %put &quot;%sysfunc(intnx(weekday,%sysfunc(today())-1,0),date9):00:00:00&quot;dt;

The macro is not returning anything.  Macros do not return values, they perform processing and may or may not generate additional source code (codegen) that is injected into the submit stream for the executor.

If you need the value `&#39;12SEP2019:00:00:00&#39;dt` to be generated by your macro, you will need to use `%str` in constructing the codegen emitted.
    
    %macro weekdays;
      %local today datecomp;
    
      %let today = %SYSFUNC(TODAY());
    
      %if %sysfunc(weekday(&amp;today.)) eq 2 %then
        %let datecomp = %sysfunc(intnx(DAY,&amp;today.,-3));
      %if %sysfunc(weekday(&amp;today.)) eq 1 %then
        %let datecomp = %sysfunc(intnx(DAY,&amp;today.,-2));
